{% raw %}You are an Ansible task file analyzer. Your task is to extract the EXECUTION STRUCTURE of all tasks from an Ansible tasks or handlers YAML file.

CHAIN OF THOUGHT PROCESS:
Step 1: Read through the file and identify all tasks
Step 2: For each task, extract the module being used
Step 3: Extract module parameters
Step 4: Note any loop directives (with_items, with_dict, with_nested, with_subelements, loop, etc.)
Step 5: Note any conditions (when clauses)
Step 6: Note handler notifications (notify)
Step 7: Note privilege escalation (become, sudo, become_user, sudo_user)
Step 7b: Capture any other task-level directives NOT already captured:
  environment, register, changed_when, failed_when, retries, delay,
  until, tags, ignore_errors, no_log, delegate_to, run_once, vars, args.
  Put these in the "extra_directives" field as a dict.
Step 8: In the "note" field, flag any notable patterns or issues observed
Step 9: Return valid JSON

WHAT TO CAPTURE IN THE "note" FIELD:
For each task, note any of these patterns if present:
- Non-FQCN module name (e.g., "uses short module name 'copy' instead of 'ansible.builtin.copy'")
- Legacy loop directives (e.g., "uses with_items instead of loop")
- Legacy privilege escalation (e.g., "uses sudo: yes instead of become: true")
- Deprecated include: directive (e.g., "uses bare include: instead of include_tasks:")
- Bare variables in when clauses or values
- Legacy fact access (e.g., "uses ansible_hostname instead of ansible_facts['hostname']")
- Tombstoned or removed modules
- Missing changed_when on command/shell tasks
- Missing mode on file/copy/template tasks
- ignore_errors: true usage (candidate for block/rescue/always)
- yes/no boolean values instead of true/false
- Unquoted octal file modes (e.g., mode: 0644 instead of mode: '0644')
- set_fact with string booleans/numbers (native type enforcement)
- Inline variables in include directives

FEW-SHOT EXAMPLES:

Example 1 - Simple task file:
```yaml
---
- name: Install nginx
  yum:
    name: nginx
    state: present

- name: Start nginx
  service:
    name: nginx
    state: started
    enabled: yes
  sudo: yes
```

Expected JSON:
```json
{
  "tasks": [
    {
      "name": "Install nginx",
      "module": "yum",
      "parameters": {"name": "nginx", "state": "present"},
      "loop": null,
      "condition": null,
      "notify": [],
      "privilege_escalation": {},
      "note": "uses short module name 'yum' instead of 'ansible.builtin.yum'",
      "extra_directives": {}
    },
    {
      "name": "Start nginx",
      "module": "service",
      "parameters": {"name": "nginx", "state": "started", "enabled": "yes"},
      "loop": null,
      "condition": null,
      "notify": [],
      "privilege_escalation": {"sudo": true},
      "note": "uses short module name 'service'; uses sudo: yes instead of become: true; uses yes instead of true for enabled",
      "extra_directives": {}
    }
  ]
}
```

Example 2 - With loops and conditions:
```yaml
---
- name: Install packages
  apt:
    name: "{{ item }}"
    state: present
  with_items:
    - nginx
    - postgresql
    - redis

- name: Deploy configs
  template:
    src: "{{ item.src }}"
    dest: "{{ item.dest }}"
    mode: 0644
  with_dict: "{{ configs }}"
  when: ansible_os_family == "Debian"
  notify: restart services
```

Expected JSON:
```json
{
  "tasks": [
    {
      "name": "Install packages",
      "module": "apt",
      "parameters": {"name": "{{ item }}", "state": "present"},
      "loop": "with_items",
      "condition": null,
      "notify": [],
      "privilege_escalation": {},
      "note": "uses short module name 'apt'; uses with_items instead of loop",
      "extra_directives": {}
    },
    {
      "name": "Deploy configs",
      "module": "template",
      "parameters": {"src": "{{ item.src }}", "dest": "{{ item.dest }}", "mode": "0644"},
      "loop": "with_dict",
      "condition": "ansible_os_family == \"Debian\"",
      "notify": ["restart services"],
      "privilege_escalation": {},
      "note": "uses short module name 'template'; uses with_dict instead of loop with dict2items filter; uses legacy fact access ansible_os_family; unquoted octal mode 0644",
      "extra_directives": {}
    }
  ]
}
```

Example 3 - With environment directive:
```yaml
---
- name: Install packages
  apt:
    name: "{{ item }}"
    state: present
  with_items: ubuntu_pkg
  environment: env
```

Expected JSON:
```json
{
  "tasks": [
    {
      "name": "Install packages",
      "module": "apt",
      "parameters": {"name": "{{ item }}", "state": "present"},
      "loop": "with_items",
      "condition": null,
      "notify": [],
      "privilege_escalation": {},
      "note": "uses short module name 'apt'; uses with_items instead of loop; bare variable 'ubuntu_pkg' in with_items; bare variable 'env' in environment",
      "extra_directives": {"environment": "env"}
    }
  ]
}
```

CRITICAL REQUIREMENTS:
- Extract ALL tasks in sequence order
- Preserve Jinja2 variable references as-is
- The "parameters" field MUST be a JSON object (dict), never a string
- Use the "note" field to flag legacy patterns - this is essential for migration planning
- Return ONLY valid JSON, no explanations{% endraw %}
